00:02:47.919 --> 00:02:49.539
So what is web accessibility about?

00:02:49.539 --> 00:02:56.349
Well, before we set out to discover what web
accessibility is, it is important to look

00:02:56.349 --> 00:02:59.409
at what accessibility itself is all about.

00:02:59.409 --> 00:03:01.840
So what is accessibility?

00:03:01.840 --> 00:03:05.009
Well, when you set out to define accessibility,

00:03:05.009 --> 00:03:11.769
you immediately encounter the biggest problem
surrounding the subject and the problem is

00:03:11.770 --> 00:03:18.960
that accessibility is a very broad,
very vague, very hard to define concept.

00:03:18.960 --> 00:03:26.909
However, Joe Clark, an accessibility consultant and author,
once said to me, and he may have put it best when he said,

00:03:26.909 --> 00:03:35.409
accessibility is making allowances for that
which you can't change or can't change easily.

00:03:35.409 --> 00:03:44.180
Now this gives us a great feel for what the essence of
accessibility is all about, but it's still pretty obscure.

00:03:44.180 --> 00:03:46.700
It's not very pragmatic.

00:03:46.699 --> 00:03:49.089
So then what is accessibility?

00:03:49.090 --> 00:03:53.460
Well accessibility first and foremost is about people.

00:03:53.460 --> 00:03:57.260
Accessibility really is about people with disabilities.

00:03:57.259 --> 00:03:59.539
So then how many people are we talking about here?

00:03:59.539 --> 00:04:05.789
Well, worldwide we're talking about
more than 600 million people.

00:04:05.789 --> 00:04:10.669
600 million people in the world with
some kind of physical disability.

00:04:10.669 --> 00:04:12.829
That's over 9% of our population.

00:04:12.830 --> 00:04:16.900
But the percentage is even way higher
than that in first world countries.

00:04:16.899 --> 00:04:22.539
In the United States, there's over
54 million people with a disability,

00:04:22.540 --> 00:04:26.170
which is almost 1 in every 5 people in the country.

00:04:26.170 --> 00:04:32.660
And first world countries report higher percentages
because they have better reporting available to them.

00:04:32.660 --> 00:04:37.100
They have better amenities for
people to live with a disability.

00:04:37.100 --> 00:04:43.340
So, people with a disability the numbers are very high.

00:04:43.339 --> 00:04:45.459
So what types of disabilities are we talking about here.

00:04:45.459 --> 00:04:49.019
Well there's four main types of physical disabilities.

00:04:49.019 --> 00:04:51.560
The first one is visual impairment.

00:04:51.560 --> 00:04:58.949
Someone is either blind, has partial sight, also
color blindness which effects 8% of all men.

00:04:58.949 --> 00:05:04.060
What may seem like some nice set of
colors to you can be very hard to read

00:05:04.060 --> 00:05:07.600
for someone with a specific color blindness.

00:05:07.600 --> 00:05:09.910
There's also a dexterity impairment.

00:05:09.910 --> 00:05:14.910
It may be difficult for someone to hold a mouse, or hold
the mouse steady enough to click on very small links.

00:05:14.910 --> 00:05:20.230
Someone may not be able to hold the mouse at
all, and have to rely on keyboard navigation.

00:05:20.230 --> 00:05:29.180
Or they may be so motor impaired that they have to use
voice commands to navigate your website, their computer.

00:05:29.180 --> 00:05:31.030
There's also hearing impairment.

00:05:31.029 --> 00:05:36.619
Now, you may think, well with all this text on the
web how does hearing impairment really have an effect?

00:05:36.620 --> 00:05:40.439
Well we're getting into more and
more multimedia content on the web.

00:05:40.439 --> 00:05:49.990
We are getting a large amount of podcast, lots of video
content, and if all that content isn't properly transcribed

00:05:49.990 --> 00:05:54.699
or captioned, then people who can't
hear are locked out of the content.

00:05:54.699 --> 00:05:56.519
This is becoming increasingly the case.

00:05:56.519 --> 00:05:59.599
And then there's learning impairment.

00:05:59.600 --> 00:06:06.320
And learning impairment is a very, very wide array
of possible disabilities, but one of them that I want

00:06:06.319 --> 00:06:08.480
to highlight is the language of your website.

00:06:08.480 --> 00:06:14.759
Now if you are building an English language website, someone
who is visiting it may not be a native English speaker.

00:06:14.759 --> 00:06:22.409
And if you are using a lot of high level complex English
language in your site, someone who is not a native speaker,

00:06:22.410 --> 00:06:26.590
may not be able to really comprehend
what your website is all about.

00:06:26.589 --> 00:06:33.589
The same if you use a lot of jargon, a lot of slang,
abbreviations, or acronyms and you don't define these terms

00:06:33.589 --> 00:06:39.089
that you are using then someone who is not
familiar with them may just give up and leave.

00:06:39.089 --> 00:06:45.709
So that's physical disabilities, but
on the web, there's so much more to it.

00:06:45.709 --> 00:06:51.000
On the web, you also deal with what are
called device specific disabilities.

00:06:51.000 --> 00:06:53.189
Now these come in many, many flavors.

00:06:53.189 --> 00:06:58.579
You have the choice of web browsers someone may
be using an older version of Internet Explorer,

00:06:58.579 --> 00:07:03.310
someone may be on an old operating
system, can't even use a modern browser.

00:07:03.310 --> 00:07:05.879
Browser settings also matter very much.

00:07:05.879 --> 00:07:08.779
Whether certain features are disabled or enabled.

00:07:08.779 --> 00:07:12.089
Certain plug-ins available or not available.

00:07:12.089 --> 00:07:14.599
Also the screen resolution is very important.

00:07:14.600 --> 00:07:17.000
Someone may have a lower resolution screen.

00:07:17.000 --> 00:07:20.899
Not everyone is using nice widescreen displays.

00:07:20.899 --> 00:07:24.729
People are still using very old monitors.

00:07:24.730 --> 00:07:27.310
There's also the color calibration which matters.

00:07:27.310 --> 00:07:29.459
Then you have internet connection speeds.

00:07:29.459 --> 00:07:36.729
Someone who's on slower broadband or on dialup
will have to wait a long time before they can get

00:07:36.730 --> 00:07:42.970
to your very graphic rich or media rich
website, and they may get frustrated and leave.

00:07:42.970 --> 00:07:46.360
Internet connection speed is also
very important for mobile devices

00:07:46.360 --> 00:07:51.350
which are typically on WiFi or much lower network than that.

00:07:51.350 --> 00:07:56.260
And mobile devices have a lot of different things
that you have to take into account as well.

00:07:56.259 --> 00:07:57.599
They have a smaller screen.

00:07:57.600 --> 00:08:05.510
They only have a few buttons as input method
and they are a completely different environment

00:08:05.509 --> 00:08:09.819
and you still want your website to be
accessible on these, all these devices.

00:08:09.819 --> 00:08:11.379
And that's just a few examples.

00:08:11.379 --> 00:08:14.490
There's so much more out there.

00:08:14.490 --> 00:08:17.460
So, we have the moral reasons.

00:08:17.459 --> 00:08:18.719
It's the right thing to do.

00:08:18.720 --> 00:08:20.320
It's the right thing to be accessible.

00:08:20.319 --> 00:08:21.509
You have the business reasons.

00:08:21.509 --> 00:08:27.709
You don't want to lock out all these, all these people,
you don't want to lock out all these potential customers.

00:08:27.709 --> 00:08:30.299
And then there's government legislations.

00:08:30.300 --> 00:08:33.000
A lot of countries, especially
first world countries these days,

00:08:33.000 --> 00:08:39.559
have a lot of government legislation
that force you almost to be accessible.

00:08:39.559 --> 00:08:43.089
Now there's the EU Charter of Fundamental Rights in Europe.

00:08:43.090 --> 00:08:46.370
They also have the EuroAccessibility Consortium.

00:08:46.370 --> 00:08:52.560
There is the Disabilities Discrimination
Act in Australia and the United Kingdom.

00:08:52.559 --> 00:08:57.289
UK also has SENDA, the Special
Educational Needs and Disability Act.

00:08:57.289 --> 00:09:00.329
Canada has a great government online initiative.

00:09:00.330 --> 00:09:04.139
Japan has a fantastic Digital 21 Strategy.
!

00:09:04.139 --> 00:09:09.460
And then the United States has, there's a few,
there's the Americans with Disabilities Act,

00:09:09.460 --> 00:09:17.650
which last year has set a precedent where
this applies to retailers of any kind.

00:09:17.649 --> 00:09:24.509
It's not just brick and mortar retailers where
this is relevant it's also online retailers.

00:09:24.509 --> 00:09:33.649
So if you sell something on your website then you are liable
if you are not accessible by this act and then there is one

00:09:33.649 --> 00:09:39.279
that most of you are probably familiar
with and that is Section 508.

00:09:39.279 --> 00:09:44.839
So, there is all this government legislation
in the world now if you want to learn more

00:09:44.840 --> 00:09:51.000
about what your government is doing with
legislation on web accessibility or what kind

00:09:51.000 --> 00:09:57.769
of initiatives they are offering then you can go to
www.webaim.org and you can look up your country and you find

00:09:57.769 --> 00:10:01.360
out all the things specific to your country.

00:10:04.000 --> 00:10:12.070
So we have these reasons to be accessible, we have the moral
reason, the business reason, and the government reason.

00:10:12.070 --> 00:10:15.110
Well how do you make your website accessible?

00:10:17.820 --> 00:10:23.360
Oh, we have here an accessibility cocktail.

00:10:23.360 --> 00:10:31.180
And if you have no physical disabilities and you
have a modern computer, modern operating system,

00:10:31.179 --> 00:10:36.939
using a modern web browser, your
accessibility cocktail is a full glass.

00:10:36.940 --> 00:10:39.840
You have full access to all the content.

00:10:39.840 --> 00:10:46.460
But if you have a physical disability or you're stuck
on an older system, you're going to an internet cafe

00:10:46.460 --> 00:10:53.930
and you are using an older browser, then your
accessibility cocktail can be an empty glass.

00:10:53.929 --> 00:10:57.159
You have no access, you can't access the content.

00:10:57.159 --> 00:11:02.659
So how do you make this a full glass for everyone?

00:11:02.659 --> 00:11:07.629
Well you start by changing the
way you think about your website.

00:11:07.629 --> 00:11:17.500
Now we mentioned Web 2.0 at the beginning of this and this
is a phenomenon that has been going for the last few years.

00:11:17.500 --> 00:11:26.470
It has become very big, now there's also another phenomenon
that has been going on at the same time and that's podcast.

00:11:26.470 --> 00:11:29.389
Podcasts have become incredibly popular.

00:11:29.389 --> 00:11:32.360
Who here listens to at least one podcast a day?

00:11:34.519 --> 00:11:35.870
Not that many.

00:11:35.870 --> 00:11:38.970
Who here reads blogs?

00:11:40.580 --> 00:11:44.900
Who here has more than a hundred blogs in their newsreader?

00:11:47.590 --> 00:11:53.350
Well if you read a lot of blogs, you may not
be using podcasts much, but if you read blogs,

00:11:53.350 --> 00:12:02.389
which you probably do at work or in class, then you may find
yourself wanting to get access to this content as a podcast

00:12:02.389 --> 00:12:08.210
so you can listen to this content on your
daily commute or whenever you feel like it.

00:12:08.210 --> 00:12:13.379
And you don't have to spend time reading it
you can just listen to all this blog content.

00:12:13.379 --> 00:12:21.689
Well if you think of your website as a podcast, you get
this completely different way of thinking about the website.

00:12:21.690 --> 00:12:30.060
You get this new approach, and if you start by that, you
think well how would I think of my website as a podcast?

00:12:30.059 --> 00:12:34.489
Well, really what it means is your
website is going to be read out to you

00:12:34.490 --> 00:12:39.649
and the only thing you can control is what you hear back,
of course there is video podcast, but we don't want you,

00:12:39.649 --> 00:12:44.309
you know, watching a video podcast while you drive to work.

00:12:44.309 --> 00:12:51.679
So we have this way of thinking as
a podcast and you want your website,

00:12:51.679 --> 00:12:54.589
when it gets read out to you, you want it to make sense.

00:12:54.590 --> 00:13:00.769
You want to know that, well you want your website to
tell you this is the list that I am approaching now.

00:13:00.769 --> 00:13:06.079
Now imagine that you're using a tool to
listen to this podcast and you have a button

00:13:06.080 --> 00:13:11.860
that says well anytime I encounter a link and
I want to follow that link I click this button

00:13:11.860 --> 00:13:16.080
so you can navigate your website just by
clicking a button whenever you encounter a link.

00:13:16.080 --> 00:13:23.100
Well, if you navigate your podcast that way, your website
has a podcast you still want to know what everything means.

00:13:23.100 --> 00:13:29.740
You want to encounter well this is a heading; you
want your site to read out to you this is a list.

00:13:29.740 --> 00:13:34.259
So you want to make sure that you can actually
get all that content back to you as a podcast.

00:13:34.259 --> 00:13:38.710
This is a great way to start thinking
about web accessibility.

00:13:38.710 --> 00:13:44.889
You just get into this completely different
mindset about how to make an accessible website.

00:13:44.889 --> 00:13:47.480
So we want to make this a full glass for everyone.

00:13:47.480 --> 00:13:48.269
Well how do you that?

00:13:48.269 --> 00:13:57.730
There are three pillars of web development basically,
three pillars and you want them to be done well

00:13:57.730 --> 00:14:02.100
and these three pillars are your content, all
the data that you want to present to the user,

00:14:02.100 --> 00:14:04.879
all the things all the information on your website.

00:14:04.879 --> 00:14:06.179
You have the presentation.

00:14:06.179 --> 00:14:13.179
This is how you present it to your users, whether
it is as speech or just visually in a brochure.

00:14:13.179 --> 00:14:16.809
And you have your interactivity, your behavior.

00:14:16.809 --> 00:14:20.779
Now how do you make an accessible
website with these where you want

00:14:20.779 --> 00:14:25.529
to separate your content, your
presentation, and your behavior?

00:14:25.529 --> 00:14:28.659
And when you do you that you build them separately.

00:14:28.659 --> 00:14:33.480
You build content using semantic markup, that's your HTML.

00:14:33.480 --> 00:14:42.360
Then you want to create your presentation using cascading
style sheets, your CSS, and then you want to add a layer

00:14:42.360 --> 00:14:46.700
of behavior to it and for that you
want to use progressive enhancements.

00:14:46.700 --> 00:14:47.790
That's your Java script.

00:14:47.789 --> 00:14:52.779
And you want to separate these, well what
does that really mean, the separation?

00:14:52.779 --> 00:14:59.179
Basically it means that you take
this and you turn it into this.

00:14:59.179 --> 00:15:08.189
You take your mixed code and you separate it into
clean markup, clean CSS, and clean Java script.

00:15:08.190 --> 00:15:17.260
So you want to separate your content presentation
and behavior, what do you get out of that?

00:15:17.259 --> 00:15:19.519
You get the benefit of file caching.

00:15:19.519 --> 00:15:28.139
If you have your contents separated into separate
files, then all these external files they are cached

00:15:28.139 --> 00:15:33.949
in the browser, they are downloaded only once by
the browser, and then retrieved from the cache

00:15:33.950 --> 00:15:38.910
so the user doesn't have to constantly
download everything on every page,

00:15:38.909 --> 00:15:42.740
this gives you the benefit of much smaller page sizes.

00:15:42.740 --> 00:15:52.190
Now this has two direct benefits - one for the user, the
user has to download less so they get to your page faster,

00:15:52.190 --> 00:15:55.330
they get a better user experience out of your website.

00:15:55.330 --> 00:16:00.700
For you it means, lower traffic costs
and this can be pretty significant.

00:16:03.960 --> 00:16:11.670
A few years ago espn.com did a
complete redesign of their website.

00:16:11.669 --> 00:16:20.159
They took their entire website and they changed it to be
built with separated content presentation and behavior.

00:16:20.159 --> 00:16:26.969
As a result, their website every page
was about 50 kilobytes smaller every page

00:16:26.970 --> 00:16:31.779
and at the time they served over
40 million page views a day.

00:16:31.779 --> 00:16:41.669
So the bandwidth savings they got out of that
were 2 terabytes a day, 61 terabytes a month,

00:16:41.669 --> 00:16:47.399
or 730 terabytes of bandwidth a
year and that's a lot of savings.

00:16:47.399 --> 00:16:52.929
So the bigger and more popular your website
is the more these savings really add up.

00:16:52.929 --> 00:16:54.929
So you get these benefits.

00:16:54.929 --> 00:16:59.099
You also get the benefit of increased reusability of code.

00:16:59.100 --> 00:17:04.279
With separation, your code becomes more usable and reusable.

00:17:04.279 --> 00:17:09.970
You can more easily include the same elements of a
design, the same elements of a page in another page

00:17:09.970 --> 00:17:15.610
because it is all separated, you can
reuse your codes in many more ways.

00:17:15.609 --> 00:17:21.549
You'll also get great maintenance benefits.

00:17:21.549 --> 00:17:27.680
When everything is separated and you need to make a
change somewhere to the visual design or to the behavior,

00:17:27.680 --> 00:17:32.700
you only have one location or you have
one file where you have to make a change

00:17:32.700 --> 00:17:35.830
so your maintainability becomes so much better.

00:17:35.829 --> 00:17:39.960
It is so much easier to maintain your website along the way.

00:17:41.029 --> 00:17:46.410
And this also helps to future proof your
website, well how does that really work?

00:17:46.410 --> 00:17:53.370
Any time a new device comes out in the future, a
completely new device, something new that we don't know yet,

00:17:53.369 --> 00:17:59.750
something new we haven't encountered yet, but it has
a capability of browsing the web, then you may find

00:17:59.750 --> 00:18:02.599
that it doesn't work as well with your website.

00:18:02.599 --> 00:18:10.659
Your website doesn't render right or any new device that
comes out as of today has to support at least a baseline

00:18:10.660 --> 00:18:13.759
of standards, and this baseline
of standards that is supported

00:18:13.759 --> 00:18:21.390
by all current browsers, all modern browsers, have the
same baseline and any new device has to support at least

00:18:21.390 --> 00:18:25.820
that baseline if it wants to survive in the market.

00:18:25.819 --> 00:18:36.189
Now it may extend the features, it may add or offer more
functionality than a regular device or a regular browser,

00:18:36.190 --> 00:18:41.289
but it has to support at least its
baseline of standards and because of that,

00:18:41.289 --> 00:18:49.099
if you have your code cleanly separated, then you can much
more easily add another little file or another piece of code

00:18:49.099 --> 00:18:53.089
to add compatibility with this new device.

00:18:53.089 --> 00:18:59.849
So it helps to future proof your website; makes it much
easier to accommodate new devices that are yet to come out.

00:19:01.160 --> 00:19:03.200
So how does that look like in code?

00:19:03.200 --> 00:19:08.580
Well this is a code example for, you
may have seen this in the past a table

00:19:08.579 --> 00:19:12.319
of navigation, just a horizontal navigation menu.

00:19:12.319 --> 00:19:13.740
Well what do we have here?

00:19:13.740 --> 00:19:18.039
We have a table element with some table rows and table cells

00:19:18.039 --> 00:19:22.129
for something that's not tabular
data at all, it is a navigation list.

00:19:22.130 --> 00:19:24.930
We have a link that doesn't point anywhere.

